<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Clock_group.svg" class=3D"mw-=
file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/common=
s/thumb/a/a4/Clock_group.svg/330px-Clock_group.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" =
width=3D"280" height=3D"123" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"5=
60" data-file-height=3D"245"></a><figcaption>Time-keeping on this clock use=
s arithmetic modulo 12. Adding 4 hours to 9 o'clock gives 1 o'clock, since =
13 is congruent to 1 modulo 12.</figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathem=
atics">mathematics</a>, <b>modular arithmetic</b> is a system of <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic" title=3D"Arithmetic">arithmetic<=
/a> operations for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer" title=
=3D"Integer">integers</a>, other than the usual ones from elementary arithm=
etic, where numbers "wrap around" when reaching a certain value, called the=
 <b>modulus</b>. The modern approach to modular arithmetic was developed by=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss" title=3D"Ca=
rl Friedrich Gauss">Carl Friedrich Gauss</a> in his book <i><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disquisitiones_Arithmeticae" title=3D"Disquisitio=
nes Arithmeticae">Disquisitiones Arithmeticae</a></i>, published in 1801.
</p><p>A familiar example of modular arithmetic is the hour hand on a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/12-hour_clock" title=3D"12-hour clock">=
12-hour clock</a>. If the hour hand points to 7 now, then 8 hours later it =
will point to 3. Ordinary addition would result in <span class=3D"nowrap">7=
 + 8 =3D 15</span>, but  15 reads as 3 on the clock face. This is because t=
he hour hand makes one rotation every 12 hours and the hour number starts o=
ver when the hour hand passes 12. We say that 15 is <i>congruent</i> to 3 m=
odulo 12, written 15 =E2=89=A1 3 (mod 12), so that 7 + 8 =E2=89=A1 3 (mod 1=
2).=20
</p><p>Similarly, if one starts at 12 and waits 8 hours, the hour hand will=
 be at 8. If one instead waited twice as long, 16 hours, the hour hand woul=
d be on 4. This can be written as 2 =C3=97 8 =E2=89=A1 4 (mod 12). Note tha=
t after a wait of exactly 12 hours, the hour hand will always be right wher=
e it was before, so 12 acts the same as zero, thus 12 =E2=89=A1 0 (mod 12).
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Congruence">Congruence</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DModular_arithmet=
ic&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Congruence"><s=
pan>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></=
div>
<p>Given an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer" title=3D"Inte=
ger">integer</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i> =E2=89=A5 1</span>, calle=
d a <b>modulus</b>, two integers <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font=
-style:italic;">a</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-sty=
le:italic;">b</span> are said to be <b>congruent</b> modulo <span class=3D"=
texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span>, if <span class=3D"texh=
tml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> is a <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Divisor" title=3D"Divisor">divisor</a> of their differen=
ce; that is, if there is an integer <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i></span>=
 such that
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =E2=88=92 <i>b</i> =3D <i>k m</i><=
/span>.</dd></dl>
<p>Congruence modulo <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">m</span> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Congruence_relat=
ion" title=3D"Congruence relation">congruence relation</a>, meaning that it=
 is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equivalence_relation" title=
=3D"Equivalence relation">equivalence relation</a> that is compatible with =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Addition" title=3D"Addition">addit=
ion</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subtraction" title=3D"Sub=
traction">subtraction</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mul=
tiplication" title=3D"Multiplication">multiplication</a>. Congruence modulo=
 <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> is deno=
ted by
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e a\equiv b~({\text{mod }}m).}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>a</mi>
        <mo>=E2=89=A1<!-- =E2=89=A1 --></mo>
        <mi>b</mi>
        <mtext>&nbsp;</mtext>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mtext>mod&nbsp;</mtext>
        </mrow>
        <mi>m</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle a\equiv b~({\=
text{mod }}m).}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/a1124d7be9f9e1c2db6844e217c0306868c32ff0" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:15.375ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle a\=
equiv b~({\text{mod }}m).}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>The parentheses mean that <span class=3D"texhtml">(mod <i>m</i>)</span> =
applies to the entire equation, not just to the right-hand side (here, <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span>).=20
</p><p>This notation is not to be confused with the notation <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><i>b</i> mod <i>m</i></span> (without parentheses), which refers =
to the remainder of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> when divided by=
 <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span>, known as the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modulo" title=3D"Modulo">modulo</a> operation: that is=
, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i> mod <i>m</i></span> denotes the unique i=
nteger <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span> s=
uch that <span class=3D"texhtml">0 =E2=89=A4 <i>r</i> &lt; <i>m</i></span> =
and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>b</i> (mod <i>m</i>)</spa=
n>. Indeed, the expression <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i> mod <i>m</i></s=
pan> does not appear in the statement <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =E2=
=89=A1 <i>b</i> (mod <i>m</i>)</span>, since it is parsed as
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e (a\equiv b){\bmod {m}}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>a</mi>
        <mo>=E2=89=A1<!-- =E2=89=A1 --></mo>
        <mi>b</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo lspace=3D"thickmathspace" rspace=3D"thickmathspace">mod</mo>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>m</mi>
          </mrow>
        </mrow>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle (a\equiv b){\=
bmod {m}}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/0529f79b0b2b95c92bd78382deeab9e83dca2692" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:15.504ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle (a=
\equiv b){\bmod {m}}.}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>The congruence relation may be rewritten as
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =3D <i>k m</i> + <i>b</i></span>,<=
/dd></dl>
<p>explicitly showing its relationship with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Euclidean_division" title=3D"Euclidean division">Euclidean divisi=
on</a>. However, the <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> here need not =
be the remainder in the division of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span>=
 by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i>.</span> Rather, <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>a</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>b</i> (mod <i>m</i>)</span> asserts that <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> h=
ave the same <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Remainder" title=3D"R=
emainder">remainder</a> when divided by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></s=
pan>. That is,
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =3D <i>p m</i> + <i>r</i></span>,<=
/dd>
<dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i> =3D <i>q m</i> + <i>r</i></span>,</dd>=
</dl>
<p>where <span class=3D"texhtml">0 =E2=89=A4 <i>r</i> &lt; <i>m</i></span> =
is the common remainder. We recover the previous relation (<span class=3D"t=
exhtml"><i>a</i> =E2=88=92 <i>b</i> =3D <i>k m</i></span>) by subtracting t=
hese two expressions and setting <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i> =3D <i>p<=
/i> =E2=88=92 <i>q</i>.</span>
</p><p>Because the congruence modulo <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">m</span> is defined by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Divisor#Further_notions_and_facts" title=3D"Divisor">divisibil=
ity</a> by <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</spa=
n> and because <span class=3D"texhtml">=E2=88=921</span> is a <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_(ring_theory)#Integer_ring" title=3D"Unit =
(ring theory)">unit</a> in the ring of integers, a number is divisible by <=
span class=3D"texhtml">=E2=88=92<i>m</i></span> exactly if it is divisible =
by <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span>.
This means that every non-zero integer <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> may be taken as a modulus.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Examples">Examples</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DModular_arithmetic&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Examples"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In modulus 12, one can assert that:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml">38 =E2=89=A1 14 (mod 12)</span></dd></dl>
<p>because the difference is <span class=3D"texhtml">38 =E2=88=92 14 =3D 24=
 =3D 2 =C3=97 12</span>, a multiple of <span class=3D"texhtml">12</span>. E=
quivalently, <span class=3D"texhtml">38</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml">=
14</span> have the same remainder <span class=3D"texhtml">2</span> when div=
ided by <span class=3D"texhtml">12</span>.
</p><p>The definition of congruence also applies to negative values. For ex=
ample:
</p>
