<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Basic_properties">Basic pro=
perties</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DModu=
lar_arithmetic&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Ba=
sic properties"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Properties"></span>
The congruence relation satisfies all the conditions of an <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equivalence_relation" title=3D"Equivalence relatio=
n">equivalence relation</a>:
</p>
<ul><li>Reflexivity: <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>a</i> (m=
od <i>m</i>)</span></li>
<li>Symmetry: <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>b</i> (mod <i>m=
</i>)</span> if and only if <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>a=
</i> (mod <i>m</i>)</span>.</li>
<li>Transitivity: If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>b</i> (m=
od <i>m</i>)</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>c</i>=
 (mod <i>m</i>)</span>, then <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>=
c</i> (mod <i>m</i>)</span></li></ul>
<p>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sub>1</sub> =E2=89=A1 <i>b</i><sub>1=
</sub> (mod <i>m</i>)</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sub>2</su=
b> =E2=89=A1 <i>b</i><sub>2</sub> (mod <i>m</i>)</span>, or if <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>b</i> (mod <i>m</i>)</span>, then:<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Modular_arithmetic#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> + <i>k</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>b</i> + <i=
>k</i> (mod <i>m</i>)</span> for any integer <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</=
i></span> (compatibility with translation)</li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k a</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>k b</i> (mod <i>m</i>)<=
/span> for any integer <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i></span> (compatibili=
ty with scaling)</li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k a</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>k b</i> (mod <i>k m</i>=
)</span> for any integer <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i></span></li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sub>1</sub> + <i>a</i><sub>2</sub> =E2=
=89=A1 <i>b</i><sub>1</sub> + <i>b</i><sub>2</sub> (mod <i>m</i>)</span> (c=
ompatibility with addition)</li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sub>1</sub> =E2=88=92 <i>a</i><sub>2</=
sub> =E2=89=A1 <i>b</i><sub>1</sub> =E2=88=92 <i>b</i><sub>2</sub> (mod <i>=
m</i>)</span> (compatibility with subtraction)</li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sub>1</sub> <i>a</i><sub>2</sub> =E2=
=89=A1 <i>b</i><sub>1</sub> <i>b</i><sub>2</sub> (mod <i>m</i>)</span> (com=
patibility with multiplication)</li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sup><i>k</i></sup> =E2=89=A1 <i>b</i><=
sup><i>k</i></sup> (mod <i>m</i>)</span> for any non-negative integer <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i></span> (compatibility with exponentiation)</li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i>(<i>a</i>) =E2=89=A1 <i>p</i>(<i>b</i>)=
 (mod <i>m</i>)</span>, for any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Po=
lynomial" title=3D"Polynomial">polynomial</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>p<=
/i>(<i>x</i>)</span> with integer coefficients (compatibility with polynomi=
al evaluation)</li></ul>
<p>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>b</i> (mod <i>m</i>)</s=
pan>, then it is generally false that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k<sup>a</s=
up></i> =E2=89=A1 <i>k<sup>b</sup></i> (mod <i>m</i>)</span>. However, the =
following is true:
</p>
<ul><li>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>c</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>d</i> (mod <i>=CF=
=86</i>(<i>m</i>)),</span> where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=86</i></spa=
n> is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler%27s_totient_function" =
title=3D"Euler's totient function">Euler's totient function</a>, then <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sup><i>c</i></sup> =E2=89=A1 <i>a</i><sup><i>d<=
/i></sup> (mod <i>m</i>)</span>=E2=80=94provided that <span class=3D"texhtm=
l"><i>a</i></span> is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coprime" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Coprime">coprime</a> with <span class=3D"texhtm=
l"><i>m</i></span>.</li></ul>
<p>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>b</i> (mod <i>mn</i>)</=
span>, then <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>b</i> (mod <i>m</=
i>)</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>b</i> (mod <i>=
n</i>)</span>.=20
</p><p>For cancellation of common terms, we have the following rules:
</p>
<ul><li>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> + <i>k</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>b</i> +=
 <i>k</i> (mod <i>m</i>)</span>, where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i></sp=
an> is any integer, then <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>b</i=
> (mod <i>m</i>)</span>.</li>
<li>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k a</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>k b</i> (mod <i>m</i=
>)</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i></span> is coprime with <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span>, then <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =
=E2=89=A1 <i>b</i> (mod <i>m</i>)</span>.</li>
<li>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k a</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>k b</i> (mod <i>k m<=
/i>)</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i> =E2=89=A0 0</span>, then <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>b</i> (mod <i>m</i>)</span>.</=
li></ul>
<p>The last rule can be used to move modular arithmetic into division. If <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> divides <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a=
</i></span>, then <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>a</i>/<i>b</i>) mod <i>m</i> =
=3D (<i>a</i> mod <i>b m</i>) / <i>b</i></span>.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_multiplicative_=
inverse" title=3D"Modular multiplicative inverse">modular multiplicative in=
verse</a> is defined by the following rules:
</p>
<ul><li>Existence: There exists an integer denoted <span class=3D"texhtml">=
<i>a</i><sup>=E2=88=921</sup></span> such that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a=
a</i><sup>=E2=88=921</sup> =E2=89=A1 1 (mod <i>m</i>)</span> if and only if=
 <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> is coprime with <span class=3D"tex=
html"><i>m</i></span>. This integer <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sup>=
=E2=88=921</sup></span> is called a <i>modular multiplicative inverse</i> o=
f <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> modulo=
 <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span>.</li>
<li>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>b</i> (mod <i>m</i>)</=
span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sup>=E2=88=921</sup></span> exis=
ts, then <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sup>=E2=88=921</sup> =E2=89=A1 <i=
>b</i><sup>=E2=88=921</sup> (mod <i>m</i>)</span> (compatibility with multi=
plicative inverse, and, if <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =3D <i>b</i></s=
pan>, uniqueness modulo <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span>).</li>
<li>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>ax</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>b</i> (mod <i>m</i>)<=
/span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> is coprime to <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span>, then the solution to this linear congruence =
is given by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>a</i><sup>=E2=88=
=921</sup><i>b</i> (mod <i>m</i>)</span>.</li></ul>
<p>The multiplicative inverse <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=89=A1 <i=
>a</i><sup>=E2=88=921</sup> (mod <i>m</i>)</span>  may be efficiently compu=
ted by solving <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B%C3%A9zout%27s_ide=
ntity" title=3D"B=C3=A9zout's identity">B=C3=A9zout's equation</a> <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml"><i>a x</i> + <i>m y</i> =3D 1</span> for <span class=3D"tex=
html"><i>x</i></span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>y</i></span>, by using th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extended_Euclidean_algorithm" ti=
tle=3D"Extended Euclidean algorithm">Extended Euclidean algorithm</a>.
</p><p>In particular, if <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i></span> is a prime=
 number, then <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> is coprime with <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i></span> for every <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</=
i></span> such that <span class=3D"texhtml">0 &lt; <i>a</i> &lt; <i>p</i></=
span>; thus a multiplicative inverse exists for all <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><i>a</i></span> that is not congruent to zero modulo <span class=3D"texhtm=
l"><i>p</i></span>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Advanced_properties">Advanc=
ed properties</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DModular_arithmetic&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: Advanced properties"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Some of the more advanced properties of congruence relations are the fol=
lowing:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermat%27s_little_theorem"=
 title=3D"Fermat's little theorem">Fermat's little theorem</a>: If <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i></span> is prime and does not divide <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><i>a</i></span>, then <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><span style=
=3D"padding-left:0.12em;"><sup><i>p</i>=E2=88=921</sup></span> =E2=89=A1 1 =
(mod <i>p</i>)</span>.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler%27s_theorem" title=3D"Eu=
ler's theorem">Euler's theorem</a>: If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></sp=
an> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span> are coprime, then <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><span style=3D"padding-left:0.12em;"><sup><i>=CF=86<=
/i>(<i>m</i>)</sup></span> =E2=89=A1 1 (mod <i>m</i>)</span>, where <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=86</i></span> is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Euler%27s_totient_function" title=3D"Euler's totient function">Euler=
's totient function</a>.</li>
<li>A simple consequence of Fermat's little theorem is that if <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i></span> is prime, then <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i=
><sup>=E2=88=921</sup> =E2=89=A1 <i>a</i><span style=3D"padding-left:0.12em=
;"><sup><i>p</i>=E2=88=922</sup></span> (mod <i>p</i>)</span> is the multip=
licative inverse of <span class=3D"texhtml">0 &lt; <i>a</i> &lt; <i>p</i></=
span>. More generally, from Euler's theorem, if <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
a</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span> are coprime, then =
<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><span style=3D"padding-left:0.12em;"><sup>=
=E2=88=921</sup></span> =E2=89=A1 <i>a</i><span style=3D"padding-left:0.12e=
m;"><sup><i>=CF=86</i>(<i>m</i>)=E2=88=921</sup></span> (mod <i>m</i>)</spa=
n>. Hence, if <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>ax</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>1</i> (mod <i>=
m</i>)</span>, then <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>a</i><spa=
n style=3D"padding-left:0.12em;"><sup><i>=CF=86</i>(<i>m</i>)=E2=88=921</su=
p></span> (mod <i>m</i>)</span>.</li>
<li>Another simple consequence is that if <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =
=E2=89=A1 <i>b</i> (mod <i>=CF=86</i>(<i>m</i>))</span>, where <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=86</i></span> is Euler's totient function, then <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i><sup><i>a</i></sup> =E2=89=A1 <i>k</i><sup><i>b</i=
></sup> (mod <i>m</i>)</span> provided <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i></sp=
an> is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coprime" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Coprime">coprime</a> with <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></sp=
an>.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilson%27s_theorem" title=3D"W=
ilson's theorem">Wilson's theorem</a>: <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i></sp=
an> is prime if and only if <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>p</i> =E2=88=92 1)!=
 =E2=89=A1 =E2=88=921 (mod <i>p</i>)</span>.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_remainder_theorem" tit=
le=3D"Chinese remainder theorem">Chinese remainder theorem</a>: For any <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></spa=
n>  and coprime <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span>, <span class=3D"tex=
html"><i>n</i></span>, there exists a unique <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</=
i> (mod <i>mn</i>)</span> such that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=89=
=A1 <i>a</i> (mod <i>m</i>)</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=
=89=A1 <i>b</i> (mod <i>n</i>)</span>. In fact,  <span class=3D"texhtml"><i=
>x</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>b m</i><sub><i>n</i></sub><sup>=E2=88=921</sup> <i>m</i=
> + <i>a n</i><sub><i>m</i></sub><sup>=E2=88=921</sup> <i>n</i> (mod <i>mn<=
/i>)</span> where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i><sub><i>n</i></sub><sup>=
=E2=88=921</sup></span> is the inverse of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i><=
/span> modulo <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i></span> and <span class=3D"te=
xhtml"><i>n</i><sub><i>m</i></sub><sup>=E2=88=921</sup></span> is the inver=
se of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i></span> modulo <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>m</i></span>.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagrange%27s_theorem_(number_t=
heory)" title=3D"Lagrange's theorem (number theory)">Lagrange's theorem</a>=
: If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i></span> is prime and <span class=3D"te=
xhtml"><i>f</i> (<i>x</i>) =3D <i>a</i><sub>0</sub> <i>x</i><sup><i>d</i></=
