}"></span> integers are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Representa=
tive_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Representative (mathemat=
ics)">representatives</a> of their respective residue classes.=20
</p><p>It is generally easier to work with integers than sets of integers; =
that is, the representatives most often considered, rather than their resid=
ue classes.=20
</p><p>Consequently, <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>a</i> mod <i>m</i>)</span>=
 denotes generally the unique integer <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">r</span> such that <span class=3D"texhtml">0 =E2=89=A4=
 <i>r</i> &lt; <i>m</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i> =E2=89=
=A1 <i>a</i> (mod <i>m</i>)</span>; it is called the <b>residue</b> of <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> modulo&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
m</i></span>.
</p><p>In particular, <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>a</i> mod <i>m</i>) =3D (=
<i>b</i> mod <i>m</i>)</span> is equivalent to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a=
</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>b</i> (mod <i>m</i>)</span>, and this explains why "<span=
 class=3D"texhtml">=3D</span>" is often used instead of "<span class=3D"tex=
html">=E2=89=A1</span>" in this context.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Residue_systems">Residue sy=
stems</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DModula=
r_arithmetic&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Resi=
due systems"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<p>Each residue class modulo <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span> may be=
 represented by any one of its members, although we usually represent each =
residue class by the smallest nonnegative integer which belongs to that cla=
ss<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Modular_arithmetic#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (since this is the pr=
oper remainder which results from division). Any two members of different r=
esidue classes modulo <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span> are incongrue=
nt modulo <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span>. Furthermore, every integ=
er belongs to one and only one residue class modulo <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><i>m</i></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_arithmetic#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The set of integers <span class=3D"texhtml">{0, 1, 2, ..., <i>m</i> =
=E2=88=92 1}</span> is called the <b>least residue system modulo <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span></b>. Any set of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m<=
/i></span> integers, no two of which are congruent modulo <span class=3D"te=
xhtml"><i>m</i></span>, is called a <b>complete residue system modulo <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span></b>.
</p><p>The least residue system is a complete residue system, and a complet=
e residue system is simply a set containing precisely one <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Representative_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Representative (mathematics)">representative</a> of each residue =
class modulo <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_arith=
metic#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For example, the least residue system modulo =
<span class=3D"texhtml">4</span> is <span class=3D"texhtml">{0, 1, 2, 3}</s=
pan>. Some other complete residue systems modulo <span class=3D"texhtml">4<=
/span> include:
</p>
<ul><li><span class=3D"texhtml">{1, 2, 3, 4}</span></li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml">{13, 14, 15, 16}</span></li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml">{=E2=88=922, =E2=88=921, 0, 1}</span></li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml">{=E2=88=9213, 4, 17, 18}</span></li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml">{=E2=88=925, 0, 6, 21}</span></li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml">{27, 32, 37, 42}</span></li></ul>
<p>Some sets that are <i>not</i> complete residue systems modulo 4 are:
</p>
<ul><li><span class=3D"texhtml">{=E2=88=925, 0, 6, 22}</span>, since <span =
class=3D"texhtml">6</span> is congruent to <span class=3D"texhtml">22</span=
> modulo <span class=3D"texhtml">4</span>.</li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml">{5, 15}</span>, since a complete residue system=
 modulo <span class=3D"texhtml">4</span> must have exactly <span class=3D"t=
exhtml">4</span> incongruent residue classes.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Reduced_residue_systems">Re=
duced residue systems</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DModular_arithmetic&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Ed=
it section: Reduced residue systems"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reduced_residue_syst=
em" title=3D"Reduced residue system">Reduced residue system</a></div>
<p>Given the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler%27s_totient_fun=
ction" title=3D"Euler's totient function">Euler's totient function</a> <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=86</i>(<i>m</i>)</span>, any set of <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=86</i>(<i>m</i>)</span> integers that are <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coprime_integers" title=3D"Coprime integers">re=
latively prime</a> to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span> and mutually =
incongruent under modulus <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span> is called=
 a <b>reduced residue system modulo <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span>=
</b>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Modular_arithmetic#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The set <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml">{5, 15}</span> from above, for example, is an instance of a r=
educed residue system modulo&nbsp;4.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Covering_systems">Covering =
systems</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DModu=
lar_arithmetic&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Co=
vering systems"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covering_system" tit=
le=3D"Covering system">Covering system</a></div>
<p>Covering systems represent yet another type of residue system that may c=
ontain residues with varying moduli.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Integers_modulo_m">Integers=
 modulo <i>m</i></h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?tit=
le=3DModular_arithmetic&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Integers modulo m"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In the context of this paragraph, the modulus <span class=3D"texhtml"><i=
