<p>In pure mathematics, modular arithmetic is one of the foundations of <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory" title=3D"Number theory=
">number theory</a>, touching on almost every aspect of its study, and it i=
s also used extensively in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Group_t=
heory" title=3D"Group theory">group theory</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Ring_theory" title=3D"Ring theory">ring theory</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knot_theory" title=3D"Knot theory">knot t=
heory</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstract_algebra" t=
itle=3D"Abstract algebra">abstract algebra</a>. In applied mathematics, it =
is used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_algebra" title=
=3D"Computer algebra">computer algebra</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Cryptography" title=3D"Cryptography">cryptography</a>, <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_science" title=3D"Computer science"=
>computer science</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chemistry" =
title=3D"Chemistry">chemistry</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Visual_arts" title=3D"Visual arts">visual</a> and <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Music" title=3D"Music">musical</a> arts.
</p><p>A very practical application is to calculate checksums within serial=
 number identifiers. For example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
International_Standard_Book_Number" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Internat=
ional Standard Book Number">International Standard Book Number</a> (ISBN) u=
ses modulo 11 (for 10-digit ISBN) or modulo 10 (for 13-digit ISBN) arithmet=
ic for error detection. Likewise, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
International_Bank_Account_Number" title=3D"International Bank Account Numb=
er">International Bank Account Numbers</a> (IBANs) use modulo 97 arithmetic=
 to spot user input errors in bank account numbers. In chemistry, the last =
digit of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CAS_registry_number" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"CAS registry number">CAS registry number</a>=
 (a unique identifying number for each chemical compound) is a <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Check_digit" title=3D"Check digit">check digit=
</a>, which is calculated by taking the last digit of the first two parts o=
f the CAS registry number times 1, the previous digit times 2, the previous=
 digit times 3 etc., adding all these up and computing the sum modulo 10.
</p><p>In cryptography, modular arithmetic directly underpins <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public-key_cryptography" title=3D"Public-key cr=
yptography">public key</a> systems such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/RSA_(algorithm)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"RSA (algorithm)">R=
SA</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_=
key_exchange" title=3D"Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman key exchange">Diffie=E2=80=93=
Hellman</a>, and provides <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finite_f=
ield" title=3D"Finite field">finite fields</a> which underlie <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elliptic_curve" title=3D"Elliptic curve">ellipt=
ic curves</a>, and is used in a variety of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Symmetric_key_algorithm" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Symmetric =
key algorithm">symmetric key algorithms</a> including <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Advanced_Encryption_Standard" title=3D"Advanced Encrypt=
ion Standard">Advanced Encryption Standard</a> (AES), <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Data_Encryption_Algorithm" title=3D"Inter=
national Data Encryption Algorithm">International Data Encryption Algorithm=
</a> (IDEA), and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RC4" title=3D"RC4=
">RC4</a>. RSA and Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman use <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Modular_exponentiation" title=3D"Modular exponentiation">modula=
r exponentiation</a>.
</p><p>In computer algebra, modular arithmetic is commonly used to limit th=
e size of integer coefficients in intermediate calculations and data. It is=
 used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_factorization"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Polynomial factorization">polynomial factor=
ization</a>, a problem for which all known efficient algorithms use modular=
 arithmetic. It is used by the most efficient implementations of <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_greatest_common_divisor" title=3D=
"Polynomial greatest common divisor">polynomial greatest common divisor</a>=
, exact <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra" title=3D"L=
inear algebra">linear algebra</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Gr%C3%B6bner_basis" title=3D"Gr=C3=B6bner basis">Gr=C3=B6bner basis</a>=
 algorithms over the integers and the rational numbers. As posted on <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fidonet" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Fidonet">Fidonet</a> in the 1980s and archived at <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Rosetta_Code" title=3D"Rosetta Code">Rosetta Code</a>, modu=
lar arithmetic was used to disprove <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Euler%27s_sum_of_powers_conjecture" title=3D"Euler's sum of powers conjec=
ture">Euler's sum of powers conjecture</a> on a <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Sinclair_QL" title=3D"Sinclair QL">Sinclair QL</a> <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microcomputer" title=3D"Microcomputer">micro=
computer</a> using just one-fourth of the integer precision used by a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CDC_6600" title=3D"CDC 6600">CDC 6600</=
a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supercomputer" title=3D"Superco=
mputer">supercomputer</a> to disprove it two decades earlier via a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brute_force_search" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Brute force search">brute force search</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_arith=
metic#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In computer science, modular arithmetic is often applied in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bitwise_operation" title=3D"Bitwise opera=
tion">bitwise operations</a> and other operations involving fixed-width, cy=
clic <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_structure" title=3D"Data=
 structure">data structures</a>. The modulo operation, as implemented in ma=
ny <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language" title=3D"=
Programming language">programming languages</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Calculator" title=3D"Calculator">calculators</a>, is an a=
pplication of modular arithmetic that is often used in this context. The lo=
gical operator <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/XOR" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"XOR">XOR</a> sums 2 bits, modulo 2.
</p><p>The use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_division" t=
itle=3D"Long division">long division</a> to turn a fraction into a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Repeating_decimal" title=3D"Repeating dec=
imal">repeating decimal</a> in any base <i>b</i> is equivalent to modular m=
ultiplication of <i>b</i> modulo the denominator. For example, for decimal,=
 <i>b</i> =3D 10.
</p><p>In music, arithmetic modulo 12 is used in the consideration of the s=
ystem of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Twelve-tone_equal_tempera=
ment" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Twelve-tone equal temperament">twelve-=
tone equal temperament</a>, where <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Octave" title=3D"Octave">octave</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Enharmonic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Enharmonic">enharmonic</a>=
 equivalency occurs (that is, pitches in a 1:2 or 2:1 ratio are equivalent,=
 and C-<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sharp_(music)" title=3D"Sha=
rp (music)">sharp</a> is considered the same as D-<a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Flat_(music)" title=3D"Flat (music)">flat</a>).
</p><p>The method of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Casting_out_n=
ines" title=3D"Casting out nines">casting out nines</a> offers a quick chec=
k of decimal arithmetic computations performed by hand. It is based on modu=
lar arithmetic modulo 9, and specifically on the crucial property that 10 =
=E2=89=A1 1 (mod 9).
</p><p>Arithmetic modulo 7 is used in algorithms that determine the day of =
the week for a given date. In particular, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Zeller%27s_congruence" title=3D"Zeller's congruence">Zeller's congr=
uence</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doomsday_algorit=
hm" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Doomsday algorithm">Doomsday algorithm</=
a> make heavy use of modulo-7 arithmetic.
</p><p>More generally, modular arithmetic also has application in disciplin=
es such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Politics" title=3D"Poli=
tics">politics</a> (for example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A=
pportionment_(politics)" title=3D"Apportionment (politics)">apportionment</=
a>), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economics" title=3D"Economics=
">economics</a> (for example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game=
_theory" title=3D"Game theory">game theory</a>) and other areas of the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_science" title=3D"Social scienc=
e">social sciences</a>, where <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prop=
ortional_(fair_division)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Proportional (fair=
 division)">proportional</a> division and allocation of resources plays a c=
entral part of the analysis.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Computational_complexity">C=
omputational complexity</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DModular_arithmetic&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D=
"Edit section: Computational complexity"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Since modular arithmetic has such a wide range of applications, it is im=
portant to know how hard it is to solve a system of congruences. A linear s=
ystem of congruences can be solved in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Polynomial_time" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Polynomial time">polyno=
mial time</a> with a form of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gauss=
ian_elimination" title=3D"Gaussian elimination">Gaussian elimination</a>, f=
or details see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_congruence_t=
heorem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Linear congruence theorem">linear co=
ngruence theorem</a>. Algorithms, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Montgomery_reduction" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Montgomery red=
uction">Montgomery reduction</a>, also exist to allow simple arithmetic ope=
rations, such as multiplication and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Modular_exponentiation" title=3D"Modular exponentiation">exponentiation m=
odulo&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span></a>, to be performed eff=
iciently on large numbers.
</p><p>Some operations, like finding a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Discrete_logarithm" title=3D"Discrete logarithm">discrete logarithm</a=
> or a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_congruences" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Quadratic congruences">quadratic congruence</a> =
appear to be as hard as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_fa=
ctorization" title=3D"Integer factorization">integer factorization</a> and =
thus are a starting point for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryp=
tography" title=3D"Cryptography">cryptographic algorithms</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Encryption" title=3D"Encryption">encrypti=
on</a>. These problems might be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NP=
-intermediate" title=3D"NP-intermediate">NP-intermediate</a>.
</p><p>Solving a system of non-linear modular arithmetic equations is <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NP-complete" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"NP-complete">NP-complete</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_arithmetic#cite_note-9">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p>
